<H3> <TI>   Continued Reports on Issues Related to DPRK </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Continued Reports on Issues Related to DPRK </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Kakizawa on Nuclear Program </H4>

<F P=102> OW2406152794 Tokyo TOKYO SHIMBUN in Japanese 23 Jun 94 
Morning Edition p 2 --FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2406152794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo TOKYO SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] At a 22 June session of the Committee on Foreign 
Affairs of the House of Representatives, Takashi Kosugi of the 
opposition Liberal Democratic Party asked Foreign Minister Koji 
Kakizawa how he planned to deal with the issue of North Korea's 
past nuclear development and the stalled Japan-North Korea 
normalization talks. Answering the question, the foreign 
minister said: "Japan has not made it a condition for resuming 
the stalled Japan-North Korea normalization talks to clear up 
suspicions about North Korea's past nuclear development. It is, 
however, important to clear up suspicions about that country's 
nuclear development during the bilateral normalization talks 
before Japan and North Korea normalize their relations." In this 
way, he showed a positive position on resuming the stalled 
Japan-North Korea normalization talks. 
  During the session, Kosugi also proposed that Makoto Tanabe, 
former chairman of the Social Democratic Party of Japan, and 
former prime ministers be sent to North Korea for 
behind-the-scenes negotiations with North Korean officials. In 
response, Foreign Minister Kakizawa implicitly welcomed Kosugo's 
proposal, saying, "If they want to take the trouble to visit 
North Korea, we hope they will do so." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

