<H3> <TI>   Continued Reports on Issues Related to DPRK </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Continued Reports on Issues Related to DPRK </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Kakizawa on Resumption of Talks </H4>

<F P=102> OW2406154694 Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN in Japanese 23 Jun 94 
Morning Edition p 2 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2406154694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] At the lower house diplomatic committee meeting on 
22 June, Foreign Minister Koji Kakizawa commented on resumption 
of the 3d round of high-level U.S.-DPRK talks. Regarding the 
DPRK's suspected nuclear arms development plan, he said that 
Japan will not necessarily insist on the need to carry out 
inspections on the DPRK's application of plutonium for military 
purposes in the past. 
  So far, the foreign minister has been saying that it is 
important to find out whether or not the DPRK ever tried to 
develop nuclear weapons. On 22 June, however, Kakizawa 
commented on the U.S. Government's view, saying: "It seems that 
the U.S. Government plans, for the time being, not to force 
inspections on the DPRK over its history of nuclear reactor 
operation but to seek, at the high- level talks, complete 
implementation of [nuclear] inspections, including special 
inspections." He then said: "In this way, the suspicions over 
the DPRK's nuclear issues, including the doubts about the past, 
will be dissolved. We will ask the United States to keep our 
views in mind as it holds U.S.-DPRK talks." He made these 
comments in response to a question by Shouzou Harada (of the 
Liberal Democratic Party). 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

