<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Continued Reports on Issues Related to DPRK </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Continued Reports on Issues Related to DPRK </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Dietman on US-DPRK Talks </H4>

<F P=102> OW2406155994 Tokyo SANKEI SHIMBUN in Japanese 24 Jun 94 
Morning Edition p 2 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2406155994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo SANKEI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Taku Yamazaki, former director-general of the 
Defense Agency, and Yoichi Tani, acting chairman of the 
Dietmen's League for Promotion of Friendship between Japan and 
North Korea, gave a report on their recent visit to North Korea 
at the Japan Press Club in Uchisaiwai-cho, Tokyo on 21 June. 
Both of them are dietmembers from the Liberal Democratic Party. 
  Following the talks held between former U.S. President Jimmy 
Carter and President Kim Il-song, North Korea has made positive 
moves towards holding the third round of U.S.-DPRK talks, as 
well as South-North summit talks. Touching on these moves in 
his report, Yamazaki stated his view that the DPRK is shifting 
its political stance to an open-door policy. 
  However, concerning further nuclear inspections, Dietman 
Tani said: "There will possibly be a difference in views between 
nuclear and military experts. (When we suggested that they 
should accept inspections by the International Atomic Energy 
Agency,) we got no response. It certainly is not that easy." 
Thus, he expressed his view that it will be difficult for the 
United States and the DPRK to succeed in talks. 

</TEXT>

