<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Keidanren Urges Abolition of 70 Regulations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Keidanren Urges Abolition of 70 Regulations </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2706091294 Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 25 Jun 94 
Morning Edition p 9 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2706091294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] On 24 June, the Federation of Economic 
Organizations of Japan [Keidanren] (chairman Shoichiro Toyoda) 
decided to urge the government to include the complete abolition 
of 70 economic regulations, which was suggested in an interim 
report worked out by the Economic Reform Study Council (the 
Hiraiwa Council), in the five-year program for promoting 
deregulation (action program) to be formulated by the end of 
this fiscal year. 
  The 70 regulations are: 19 regulations on participation in 
business operations, such as liquor production and sales; nine 
regulations on facilities requirements, including the Large 
Retail Store Law; 23 trade regulations, such as the state trade 
items; and 19 price regulations, such as government purchase 
prices for rice and wheat. Keidanren also demands the five-year 
plan include a schedule for reducing regulations by half in five 
years, at the longest, and completely abolishing them after 10 
years. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

