<H3> <TI>   Details of Transport Deregulation Plan Revealed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Details of Transport Deregulation Plan Revealed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2406145494 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 24 Jun 
94 Morning Edition p 5 --FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2406145494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Details of a deregulation plan which the Ministry 
of Transport [MOT] will newly implement have been revealed. In 
connection with the issue of standards and certification for 
automobiles, which is a focal point of the Japan-U.S. economic 
framework talks, the MOT will improve the system of accepting 
international standards and data on foreign inspections. The 
27- item deregulation plan also includes: 1) flexible 
management of freight railway fares and warehouse charges; and 
2) expansion of business areas for trucks. The plan will be 
incorporated into a deregulation package to be compiled by the 
government at the end of June. The MOT will not introduce the 
price ceiling system (price cap system) for railway fares, 
saying "there are still many problems" in the system. The 
introduction of the system has been demanded by JR [Japan 
Railway Company] and the Administrative Reform Headquarters' 
working group on imports promotion, market access improvement, 
and distribution. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

