<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-123-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  25 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministris To Study Import Restraint Measures </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ministris To Study Import Restraint Measures </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2606222294 Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN in Japanese 25 Jun 94 
Morning Edition p 7 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2606222294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] On 24 June, the Ministry of International Trade and 
Industry [MITI] began studying concrete import restraint 
measures to be implemented when foreign products flood into 
Japanese markets. On the same day, the ministry held the first 
meeting of the Export-Import Transaction Council (an advisory 
panel to the international trade and industry minister). It 
plans to work out conclusion in time for discussions on the 
ratification of the World Trade Organization (WTO) treaty 
scheduled for September. 
  The Finance Ministry has also begun the study of import 
restraint measures at the Customs Tariff Council (an advisory 
body to the finance minister). The two ministries will work in 
closer cooperation through their councils to work out 
"Japanese-style import restraint" measures. 
  The WTO treaty, which was signed in April following the 
conclusion of the Uruguay Round of talks, authorizes a country 
to restrain imports as an emergency measure by such means as 
raising tariffs when a low-priced product is imported in large 
quantities. Although Japan has a system of imposing retaliatory 
tariffs or volume restraint, it seldom implements these measures 
because it takes a lot of time to do so in actuality. 
  The WTO treaty approves of retaliatory measures when the 
treaty is violated. For example, if a textile product is 
imported in violation of the treaty, taking retaliatory measures 
against another product, like automobiles, is possible under the 
treaty. However, Japan has not yet decided on concrete 
retaliatory measures. 
  Thus, the two councils will discuss what kind of retaliatory 
measures should be adopted. 
  They plan to review the Customs Tariff Law and the Foreign 
Exchange Control Law, if necessary. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-30415 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas123__a94019" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-123-A </AU>
