<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   G-7 `Considering' Ukraine Nuclear Plants Aid </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    G-7 `Considering' Ukraine Nuclear Plants Aid </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2406115094 Tokyo KYODO in English 0955 GMT 24 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2406115094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 24 KYODO -- The Group of Seven (G-7) 
industrialized nations are considering proposing more than 1.5 
billion dollars in aid for Ukraine as a way to ensure the safety 
of its outmoded nuclear power plants, a Japanese Government 
official said Friday [24 June]. 
  The sum, which would be proposed during the coming annual 
summit, would partly finance a plan to solidify safety shields 
of the exploded reactor at the Chernobyl nuclear power plant, 
the official said. 
  The remainder would be used to remodel several other 
reactors 
currently under construction in the former Soviet republic, the 
official said, noting that these reactors, basically identical 
in design to the exploded reactor, must be reconstructed with 
Western technology. 
  France and Germany recently proposed the aid program. 
  In April 1986, one of four reactors at the Chernobyl nuclear 
power plant exploded, resulting in the worst nuclear accident in 
history. 
  Of the three reactors left, two are still in operation, 
causing global concern over a possible repeat of the Chernobyl 
disaster. 
  During the Naples summit in July, the G-7 nations are 
expected to press for closure of the two reactors, which Ukraine 
claims are necessary as major power sources for the economically 
ailing country, the government official said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

