<F P=100> INTER-ASIAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   PRC Wants Bilateral Talks on Spratlys Issue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    PRC Wants Bilateral Talks on Spratlys Issue </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK2306063194 Quezon City Radio Filipinas in English 0230 GMT 
23 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2306063194 </F>
<F P=104>  Quezon City Radio Filipinas </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] China wants to reach a final settlement with the 
Philippines and other claimants to the Spratly Islands, but only 
through bilateral discussions and not through the international 
group like the United Nations or ASEAN. This was the stand 
conveyed by Premier Li Peng of China to a Philippine Government 
and business delegation led by Philippine Vice President Joseph 
Estrada in a meeting held in Beijing. 
  Li told Estrada that the discussions must be held with one 
country at a time, and not in a conference hosted by any 
international group. 
  Estrada noted, however, that the Philippines will stick to 
the position taken by ASEAN in 1992 -- that its members with 
claims over the Spratlys must negotiate with China and claimant 
Vietnam as a group. But Estrada showed his strong (?compose) 
that the Philippines would seek all peaceful means to resolve 
the problem. 
  Apart from the Philippines, China, and Vietnam, other 
claimants to the Spratlys are Brunei, Indonesia, and Malaysia. 

</TEXT>

