<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hata Resignation Affects International Ties </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hata Resignation Affects International Ties </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2706113894 Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN in Japanese 26 Jun 94 
Morning Edition p 3 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2706113894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] There is a growing concern within the government 
over the impact of the en masse resignation of the Hata cabinet 
on Japanese diplomacy. A Foreign Ministry source said: "The 
act indicates that the cabinet has given no importance to 
diplomacy. This will impair Japan's reputation." The anxiety 
has arisen because Japan has to deal with many 
diplomatically-important international meetings next month. 
These include the Japan-U.S. summit, the Naples summit (G-7 
summit talks), and the "ASEAN regional forum," where the first 
Asia-Pacific region security talks will be held. 
  At a 25 June news conference, Foreign Minister Koji Kakizawa 
said: "It is very regrettable that at this juncture, we cannot 
deal fully with important diplomatic issues because of political 
confusion at home." In particular, the government is concerned 
about the upcoming G-7 summit. Last year, (then) Prime Minister 
Kiichi Miyazawa was already a "lame duck" when he attended the 
Tokyo summit because he was forced to dissolve the House of 
Representatives for a snap general election immediately after 
the summit ended. The same Foreign Ministry source expressed 
anxiety, saying that the political confusion occurring just 
before the summits for two consecutive years "will had a 
detrimental effect on Japan's position in the international 
community." 
  G-7 summits are an ideal place to promote diplomacy among 
the 
leaders of the industrialized nations. Thus, the source said: 
"Repeated changes of government make it difficult to establish 
relations of trust between the Japanese prime minister and the 
leaders of other G-7 nations." Immediately before the G-7 
summit, the Japan-U.S. summit meeting is scheduled to mend 
bilateral ties, which have worsened since the breakdown of trade 
negotiations in February. Therefore, if elections for the next 
prime minister are delayed and as a result, if the government 
has to deal with the summit meeting with the virtual "absence of 
a prime minister," this will apparently be disadvantageous to 
Japanese diplomacy. 
  Many people question the idea of electing the new prime 
minister from among the members of the Social Democratic Party 
[SDPJ]. A top Foreign Ministry official said: "In view of 
diplomatic consistency, the idea is questionable." In 
particular, it is questioned whether the government will be able 
to take concerted actions with the United States in dealing with 
North Korea's suspected nuclear program if the SDPJ takes power. 
It is a crucial period for Japanese diplomacy. The nation has 
to deal with issues concerning the Japan-U.S. security system 
and its bid to become a permanent member of the UN Security 
Council. Thus, there is a strong call for establishing a stable 
government for the sake of Japanese diplomacy. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-30474 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas124__a94006" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-124-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  25 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shinseito's Watanabe on Talks With SDPJ </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shinseito's Watanabe on Talks With SDPJ </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2706164294 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 25 Jun 
94 Evening Edition p 2 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2706164294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Kozo Watanabe, acting secretary general of 
Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party], held a news conference on the 
afternoon of 25 June and disclosed that the party plans to 
promptly wrap up policy consultations between the ruling 
coalition parties and the Social Democratic Party of Japan 
[SDPJ]. He indicated the party seeks to form a new coalition 
government that excludes the Liberal Democratic Party before the 
Naples summit which is to start on 8 July. Regarding the 
framework of the new government, Watanabe said: "We would like 
to treat with respect the feelings of the large majority of 
upper and lower house members who voted for `Tsutomu Hata' [as 
prime minister]." He thus expressed strong hopes for the SDPJ 
and the Sakigake [Harbinger Party] to return to the coalition. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

