<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government To Ask China To Abolish Import Rules </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government To Ask China To Abolish Import Rules </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2706001394 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 25 Jun 
94 Morning Edition p 5 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2706001394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The government will ask China to abolish its import 
regulations in connection with a working group meeting on GATT 
membership which is scheduled to be held in Geneva on 27 June. 
Japan has already submitted a list of items to China on which it 
has requested tariffs should be lowered. It will also start 
full- fledged negotiations in the non-tariff field. 
  China has adopted an import quota system for wide-ranging 
products, including automobiles, home electrical appliances, and 
textile goods. In bilateral negotiations which are to be held 
to coincide with the working group meeting, Japan will urge 
China to abolish this system, saying it is questionable under 
GATT rules. Regarding non-tariff barriers, the government will 
call for market opening in such fields as the trading business 
in which Japan is very interested. Japan submitted a 3,300-item 
list to China in March requesting tariff cuts, and received a 
reply in May. However, since the reply was insufficient, Japan 
intends to ask to China to take further measures to lower 
tariffs by submitting the additional 300-item list. 

</TEXT>

