<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Stone Plate Praising Kim Chong-il Found in South </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Stone Plate Praising Kim Chong-il Found in South </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2506104794 Pyongyang KCNA in English 1007 GMT 25 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2506104794 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, June 25 (KCNA) -- A stone plate bearing 
words about the birth of the dear leader Comrade Kim Chong-il 
written 50 years ago appeared recently in Taegu, the Seoul-based 
radio Voice of National Salvation reported. 
  A scroll bearing the words "The bright star of Paektu is for 
independence of Korea. Let us uphold the bright star for the 
liberation of Korea and for the world generation after 
generation. 1944" was already discovered in Chorwon County, 
South Korean Kangwon Province, on February 10, 1994, the New 
Year's day of the lunar calendar. 
  An old man surnamed Ri, a retired professor of Kyongbuk 
National University in Taegu, on June 12 showed a round stone 
plate 15 centimetres in diametre he had kept carefully. Written 
on the stone with a writing brush are the words "O Korea, boast 
worldwide of the birth of the bright star of Paektu, successor 
to General Kim Il-song. 1944." 
  He said he found the stone, announcing the auspicious event 
of the nation, lying on the wooden floor under the eave of his 
house when he opened the door one morning in August 1944. At 
that time, a rumour was afloat that a big stone bearing the 
words "Long live the independence of Korea. Kim Il-song is 
coming" was found in front of the gate of the house of the chief 
judge of the Taegu district court. 
  "This stone plate is a most precious national treasure 
because it tells about the intense joy of our fellow countrymen 
at the news of the birth of the dear leader Kim Chong-il, and 
the historical fact that they highly praised him as the bright 
star of Paektu and the sun of the future," the old man stressed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

