<H3> <TI>   Daily Denounces South's Action Against Strikers </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Daily Denounces South's Action Against Strikers </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2606090794 Pyongyang KCNA in English 0823 GMT 26 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2606090794 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Reckless Fascist Outrage" -- KCNA headline] </F>
  [Text] Pyongyang, June 26 (KCNA) -- The South Korean police 
recently mobilized a huge force to brutally suppress rail 
workers affiliated with the National Council of Locomotive 
Workers on a sit- in strike for wage hike and improvement of 
working conditions. 
  In this regard, NODONG SINMUN today says this is an illegal 
fascist outrage and inconsiderable fascist violence. 
  The news analyst says: 
  The council urged the authorities to raise its workers' 
wages, improve the working conditions and reinstate the expelled 
workers. This, the minimum demand of the workers for their 
existence as human beings, should have been met by the South 
Korean authorities. 
  Nevertheless, the South Korean rulers have put workers on 
the 
altar of suppression, refusing to accept their just demand. 
Then, how can their behavior be construed? 
  It is ridiculous for the South Korean rulers, the guilty 
party, to threaten that they would "bring legal actions" against 
innocent workers, charging them with the "railway paralysis." 
  The fascists are calling the workers' sit-in an "illegal 
violence" and blaming them for the "railway paralysis," 
motivated by a criminal intention to shift onto the workers the 
responsibility for all the grave consequences to be entailed by 
the railway paralysis and harshly suppress and penalize them. 
  The fascist suppression leads to self-destruction. 
  The South Korean authorities would be well advised to 
promptly stop the fascist suppression, clearly mindful that the 
more harshly they crack down on the people, the more fiercely 
the people resist. 

</TEXT>

