<F P=100> Laos </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Leaves for Visit to SRV </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Minister Leaves for Visit to SRV </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK2706140094 Vientiane Vitthayou Hengsat Radio Network in 
Lao 1200 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2706140094 </F>
<F P=104>  Vientiane Vitthayou Hengsat Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Lao </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] On the afternoon of 26 June 1994, Foreign Affairs 
Minister Somsavat Lengsavat left Vientiane for a one-week 
official visit to the SRV. The visit, scheduled from 26 June to 
3 July, is aimed at holding consultations with the Vietnamese 
side on issues of common interest. It is also intended to 
strengthen the traditional solidarity and friendship between the 
foreign affairs ministries of Laos and Vietnam as well as 
between the parties, states, and peoples of the two countries. 
  After the one-week visit to Vietnam, Somsavat Lengsavat will 
proceed to the Kingdom of Cambodia for an official visit. 
Scheduled from 4 to 7 July, this visit is in response to an 
invitation of Prince Kromkhun Norodom Sirivut, deputy prime 
minister, minister of foreign affairs, and chairman of the Joint 
Cambodian-Lao Cooperation Committee. Somsavat Lengsavat will 
visit Cambodia on this occasion as chairman of the Joint 
Lao-Cambodian Cooperation Committee. It will reciprocate the 
visit to Laos by Prince Kromnkhun Norodom Sirivut in February 
1994. During the visit, Somsavat Lengsavat will discuss with 
the Cambodian side bilateral cooperation in various fields. The 
visit is also aimed at further strengthening the long-standing 
solidarity and friendship between the two countries. 
  Somsavat Lengsavat, minister of foreign affairs and chairman 
of the Joint Lao-Cambodian Cooperation Committee, was seen off 
at the airport by deputy ministers of foreign affairs. Bui Van 
Thanh and Khek Lerang, respectively ambassadors of Vietnam and 
the Kingdom of Cambodia to Laos, along with a number of 
high-ranking officials of the Foreign Affairs Ministry, were 
also on hand to see the foreign affairs minister off at the 
airport. 

</TEXT>

