<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Burma </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister Discusses Economic Issues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Minister Discusses Economic Issues </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2306145294 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 21 Jun 
94 Evening Edition p 5 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2306145294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By correspondent Atsuki Maeyama] </F>
  [Text] Rangoon, 21 June -- David Abel, Burma's minister of 
national planning and economic development, told a Keidanren 
[Japan Federation of Economic Organizations] economic mission 
(headed by Marubeni Corp. Chairman Kazuo Haruna) that the 
Burmese Government plans to enact "a privatization law" to 
promote a shift toward a market-oriented economy and facilitate 
foreign capital inflow. The Keidanren mission is currently 
visiting Burma. The minister also said the government will take 
measures to enable foreign firms to acquire state-run 
corporations. 
  The Burmese Government has said if a privatization law is 
enacted, state-run corporations will be able to establish joint 
companies with foreign firms in various industries, and foreign 
firms will be able to have capital stakes in state-run 
corporations. The country has already enacted a foreign 
investment law and a domestic investment law. However, it has 
not had a comprehensive law on joint ventures in Burma. 
  The Keidanren mission also met with Khin Nyunt, first 
secretary of the State Law and Order Restoration Council 
(SLORC). In the meeting, Nyun called on Japan to actively 
invest in Burma's agricultural and forestry industries, and in 
programs to exploit natural resources. He also asked Japanese 
companies to bear the costs for constructing hotels for the sake 
of Burma's tourist development. 
  In response, Haruna first stressed the need for Burma to 
further promote democratization, and said: "Although the 
Japanese Government's Official Development Assistance (ODA) to 
Burma has virtually been suspended (except for humanitarian 
purposes), the private sector will work to promote economic 
cooperation, while observing developments in your country." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-30557 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas124__a94002" </HT>


