Daily Report 
<DATE1>  28 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Thailand </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Stand Expected To Undermine Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S. Stand Expected To Undermine Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK2806103194 Bangkok PHUCHATKAN in Thai 28 Jun 94 p 6 </F>
<F P=103> BK2806103194 </F>
<F P=104>  Bangkok PHUCHATKAN </F>
<F P=105>  Thai </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] According to a Communications Ministry report on the 
progress of the Thai-U.S. aviation talks, the United States sent 
a letter to the ministry announcing a change in the head of the 
U.S. delegation to the negotiations and asking to extend the 
two-day talks an additional day to 30 June. 
  The United States was reportedly not satisfied with the 
results of the last rounds of talks and therefore decided to 
appoint Mr. Thomas Mark [preceding three words in English] as 
leader of its delegation. It was reported earlier that the 
United States was unhappy with the U.S. delegation's lenient 
attitude in conducting aviation talks with Thailand and other 
countries in this region. With this change in the leadership of 
the U.S. delegation, the U.S. delegation's attitude is expected 
to become more aggressive and uncompromising. 
  Touching on the U.S. request to extend the negotiations with 
the Thai delegation, Sisuk Chantharangsu, head of the Thai 
delegation and director general of the Civil Aviation 
Department, said he cannot grant the request because he will be 
engaged in official business on 30 June. Meanwhile, the Thai 
side's conditions and positions remain unchanged. Regarding the 
third airline freedom, the Thai side demands at least 55 percent 
of through passenger traffic load and 70 percent of cargo on 
U.S. planes as the conditions for agreement on the fifth freedom. 
  It is anticipated that this round of aviation talks will not 
lead to any progress because of the ambiguity and rigid attitude 
of the U.S. side. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-30561 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas124_q_94001" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-124 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  25 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> AUSTRALASIA </F>
<F P=101> Australia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Evans on Decision To Send Troops to Rwanda </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Evans on Decision To Send Troops to Rwanda </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2506181994 Melbourne Radio Australia in English 1700 GMT 
25 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2506181994 </F>
<F P=104>  Melbourne Radio Australia </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Foreign Affairs Minister Gareth Evans says it would 
be irresponsible if Australia rushed into making a decision on 
whether to send troops to Rwanda as part of a United Nations 
peacekeeping mission. The government has deferred a decision 
and instead has sent a five-person reconnaissance team to assess 
the situation in the strife-torn central African nation. 
Senator Evans says this is not an unreasonable response to what 
could be a very risky endeavor. 
  [Begin Evans recording] The situation is simply so complex, 
so messy, so uncertain, that I think we would be irresponsible 
if we made any firmer decision than that before knowing how it's 
going to pan out. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

