<DOCNO> FBIS4-30564 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas124_c_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-124 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  28 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Pyongyang, Seoul Agree To Top-Level Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Pyongyang, Seoul Agree To Top-Level Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Chief Delegate Delivers Keynote Speech </H4>

<F P=102> SK2806034494 Pyongyang Korean Central Broadcasting Network 
in Korean 0157 GMT 28 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK2806034494 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang Korean Central Broadcasting Network 
in Korean 0157 GMT 28 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=105> Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A preliminary contact for top-level talks between 
the North and the South is continuing. 
  At the contact, Kim Yong-sun, chairman of the Reunification 
Policy Committee of the Supreme People's Assembly, and head of 
our side's delegation, made a keynote speech. 
  The contents of the keynote speech are as follows: 
  Mr. Yi Hong-ku, senior delegate, and delegates of the South 
side, today we are seated together cherishing the important 
mission of preparing for North-South top-level talks. I am 
pleased that both sides are holding a preliminary contact today 
after reaching an agreement [kyonhaeui ilchirul pogo] on holding 
top-level talks. 
  We are very close to 1995, the year which all fellow 
countrymen hope will be the first year of reunification, and 
leave but one year before the 50-year mark of national division 
which we should no longer pass over. 
  However, the reality facing our nation is grave. Rather than 
removing misunderstanding, distrust, enmity, and confrontation 
between the North and the South, they have been accentuated, and 
even encouraged by outside forces. In such a situation, we were 
faced with a dangerous phase where even unstable peace 
[pulanjonghan pyonghwa] was endangered. 
  Our people are now at the crossroads of choosing one of two 
roads, either peace or war, or reunification or national common 
destruction [minjogui kongmyolinya], which cannot coexist. 
  At this solemn point, all fellow countrymen are looking to 
the patriotic determination [aegukchogin kyoltanul] of the 
top-level leaders of both sides more ardently than ever before. 
  We firmly believe that the convocation of top-level talks 
between the North and the South will be an important historic 
occasion for correctly setting the direction of our nation. 
  Delegates from the South side, the authority of top-level 
leaders of the two sides and the destiny of the nation are 
entrusted to North-South top-level talks, and the interest of 
the world is focused on these talks. 
  The North-South top-level talks should become, at any cost, 
successful talks which achieve national reconciliation and unity 
of all of the countrymen and which give a bright hope for the 
country's peace and for its independent and peaceful 
reunification. We have consistently adhered to the position of 
marking the turning point for the start towards realization of 
the country's reunification through top-level talks without 
outside forces' interference. 
  As your side knows, the respected and beloved President Kim 
Il- song personally initiated top-level talks as early as May 
1972, when North-South dialogue first began, and since then, has 
paid special attention to seeing to it that top-level talks, 
which will be of significance for the country's reunification, 
are held. 
  Our proposal for the exchange of special envoys in May last 
year was also part of our efforts for top-level talks. However, 
these efforts failed to bear due fruit. 
  It is indeed fortunate that the top-level talks which failed 
to be realized for the scores of years in the past have come to 
witness their rays for the first time today, 50 years since the 
country was divided. We think that precisely in this foundation 
lies our common position of worrying over the nation's today and 
tomorrow. We would like to believe that this position is 
precisely a manifestation of the independent spirit of shaping 
the nation's destiny with our Korean people's own strength. 
  If there are no differences in this national independent 
spirit between the North and the South, we can say that success 
of top- level talks has been guaranteed, because the top-level 
talks' ideal of linking the North and the South into one body is 
based precisely on our national, independent spirit, the source 
of our nation's will and strength to shape our destiny with our 
own strength, and the firm guarantee for defending the nation's 
common interests without falling prey to outside forces 
victimizing our nation's interests. 
  If the two sides start with this independent spirit and the 
nation's position, the North and the South will be able to 
achieve reconciliation and unity; easily transcend all 
differences in accordance with the principles of independence, 
peaceful reunification, and great national unity; overcome the 
difficult situation with the nation's united, national 
independent strength; and, thus, stand on the peak of 
reunification and prosperity which all fellow countrymen desire. 
  The North-South top-level talks that we are now going to 
have, will become the creation of a great new national history 
where the the history of antagonism that continued for half a 
century in our country changes into a history of great national 
unity; the history of confrontation becomes a history of peace; 
and the history of division becomes a history of reunification. 
It will undoubtedly give our 70 million fellow countrymen 
bright hope for reunification in the nineties and will also 
regain the great pride of our nation which has outstanding 
history, tradition, and wisdom. 
  This will also give great happiness to the world's 
peace-loving people who are worried about the situation on the 
Korean peninsula. 
  While frankly stating our basic views on the pressing 
top-level talks between the North and South, and emphasizing the 
important responsibility of both sides for the successful 
preparation of the historic top-level talks between the North 
and South, I will now put forth our proposal on the basic issues 
to be discussed at the preliminary contact. 
  First is the issue of the venue of the top-level talks. We 
propose that the venue of the top-level talks be held in 
Pyongyang. As your side knows, when President Kim Yong-sam was 
in the opposition party, the respected and beloved President Kim 
Il-song had already asked him to visit Pyongyang, and President 
Kim Yong-sam had repeatedly expressed the will that he will meet 
with President Kim Il-song, irrespective of the venue, and that 
he will visit Pyongyang. We believe that setting Pyongyang as 
the venue coincides with the will of the top-level of both sides. 
  Second is the issue of the date of the top-level talks. We 
propose to hold the top-level talks in mid-August. We believe 
that this date is significant because it is right about the day 
when the North and South all celebrate 15 August. 
  Third is the issue of the working-level procedure for the 
top- level talks between the North and South. We must discuss 
various working-level procedural issues for holding the 
top-level talks. We believe that except for important issues 
such as the venue and date, it is rational to provide a 
delegates' contact right after today's contact ends with one 
delegate from the preliminary contact of each side and two suite 
members of each side to discuss the other working-level issues. 
The delegates' contact should start from 1 July, and should be 
able to discuss issues such as the organization and scope of the 
delegation, schedule of sojourn, dispatch of advance team, 
procedures for exchange of visits, guarantee of accommodations, 
guaranteeing personal safety, and other working- level issues. 
  Fourth is the issue of creating an atmosphere for holding 
the 
top-level talks. If the talks are to be successful so that the 
top- levels of the North and South can meet, we believe that it 
is important for both sides to create a good atmosphere. Thus, 
we propose that from 1 July both sides completely stop all acts 
that may cloud the atmosphere for the top-level talks. 
  As such, while putting forth our proposal regarding the 
holding of the top-level talks between the North and South, we 
propose that an agreement on the preliminary contact for the 
top-level talks between the North and South be adopted along 
these lines so that it can be announced today. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

