<H3> <TI>   Reports on 28 Jun North-South Contact Continue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reports on 28 Jun North-South Contact Continue </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Sides `Completely' Agree on Date </H4>

<F P=102> SK2806092794 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean 0900 GMT 28 
Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK2806092794 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] At today's preliminary contact for North-South 
summit talks, the North and South completely agreed [wanjon 
habui haessumnida] to hold North-South summit talks in Pyongyang 
for three days, beginning on 25 July. Reporter Kim Chin-su will 
report from the North-South Dialogue Secretariat Office: 
  [Kim Chin-su] At today's preliminary contact for North-South 
summit talks, the North and South dramatically and completely 
agreed [kukchoguro wanjon habui haessumnida] to hold North-South 
summit talks in Pyongyang for three days from 25 July. 
  As a result, the historic North-South summit talks will 
become a reality. The two sides also agreed to discuss the 
place and timing of alternate visits to Seoul and Pyongyang by 
the top leaders of the two sides, which will be made on a 
principle of reciprocity, at the first summit talks in Pyongyang. 
  Our side's delegation led by Yi Hong-ku, deputy prime 
minister and minister of the National Unification Board, and the 
North Korean side's delegation led by Kim Yong-sun, chairman of 
the Reunification Police Committee of North Korea's Supreme 
People's Assembly, started the first preliminary talks at 1000 
today at the House of Peace, on our side's area of Panmunjom. 
[passage omitted on recap of today's meeting] 

</TEXT>

