<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kim Yong-sam Talks With Thai Prime Minister </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kim Yong-sam Talks With Thai Prime Minister </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK2506112994 Bangkok BANGKOK POST in English 25 Jun 94 pp 1, 
3 </F>

<F P=103> BK2506112994 </F>
<F P=104>  Bangkok BANGKOK POST </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Thailand and South Korea agreed yesterday to expand 
economic cooperation between their countries and increase 
regional security ties. 
  The agreement was reached during a meeting between Prime 
Minister Chuan Likphai and South Korean President Kim Young-sam. 
  The two leaders also discussed ways to ease tensions over 
North Korea's suspected diversion of plutonium to build nuclear 
weapons, officials said. 
  Prime Minister Chuan, who arrived Thursday for a four-day 
official visit wished President Kim success at the first-ever 
inter-Korean summit, which is currently being planned to help 
defuse the nuclear impasse. 
  Foreign Minister Prasong Sunsiri, reaffirming Thailand's 
support of the non-nuclear proliferation treaty, said he hoped 
North and South Korea would be able to reach an accord on the 
issue through their talks. 
  He said Bangkok hoped that North Korea would return to the 
Non-nuclear Proliferation Treaty and the United Nations' 
Security Council would not resort to harsh measures against the 
nation to force it to comply with the treaty. 
  The United States is calling on the UN Security Council to 
impose economic sanctions against North Korea and Thailand, as a 
UN member, will have to comply with any resolution, he said. 
  The Foreign Ministry's Southeast Asian Department Chief Don 
Paramatwinai quoted President Kim as saying that the nuclear 
conflict between South and North Korea posed not only a threat 
to the Korean Peninsula but the entire world. 
  The South Korean President expressed hope that the June 28 
summit would be successful. 
  South Korea was prepared to negotiate with North Korea on 
mutual interest and world security issues, Mr Don quoted 
President Kim as saying. 
  Mr Kim asked that regulations be eased to allow more South 
Korean firms to invest in construction and communications 
projects in Thailand, while Prime Minister Chuan asked that 
South Korea import more Thai agricultural goods. 
  South Korea is Thailand's seventh largest trading partner, 
with two-way trade last year totaling US$1.94 billion, a 
two-fold increase over the past five years. 
  South Korea exported US$1.47 billion worth of goods to 
Thailand last year, mostly in machinery, oil, Iron, steel, and 
automobiles, while importing sugar, computer parts, tapioca and 
rubber from Thailand. 
  The two leaders also agreed to improve South Korea's 
relations with the Association of Southeast Nations (ASEAN) 
whose members include Thailand, Malaysia, the Philippines, 
Singapore, Indonesia and Brunei. 
  During the meeting, Mr Don said President Kim also agreed in 
principle to a Thai proposal that a joint commission be set up 
between the two countries to promote trade and economic 
cooperation. 
  No actual agreement has been signed on the proposal as both 
sides would need to discuss how the commission should be formed, 
he said. 
  Prime Minister Chuan also extended an invitation to the 
South 
Korean leader to visit Thailand. 

</TEXT>

