<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Lawmaker Pak Chol-on `Guilty' of Bribe-Taking </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Lawmaker Pak Chol-on `Guilty' of Bribe-Taking </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2806070394 Seoul YONHAP in English 0621 GMT 28 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2806070394 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, June 28 (YONHAP) -- Rep. Pak Chol-on was 
found guilty of taking bribes by the Supreme Court Tuesday, 
resulting in the loss of his National Assembly seat. 
  The highest court dismissed an appeal lodged by Pak, a 
lawmaker from the United People's Party convicted earlier of 
bribery and sentenced to one and a half years in prison and 
fined 600 million won (about 743,500 U.S. dollars) at an 
appellate court on March 14. 
  Pak, once called the "crown prince" during the days of the 
No 
Tae-u government, was arrested in May last year on charges of 
taking bribes totaling 600 million won in three installments 
from the country's slot-machine kingpins -- brothers Chong 
Tok-chin and Chong Tok-il -- in October and November 1990. 
  With the Supreme Court's decision, Pak also lost the right 
to 
run for parliament or other public office for five years from 
this November when his prison term ends. This means he cannot 
run in the 15th general election slated for the first half of 
1996 and signals the likely end of his political career. 
  His application for bail was automatically rejected. 
  A by-election to replace him will be held within 90 days in 
the Susong-A electoral district of Taegu City. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

