<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Manufacturer Association: `Auto Market Is Open' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Manufacturer Association: `Auto Market Is Open' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2806112294 Tokyo KYODO in English 1007 GMT 28 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2806112294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 28 KYODO -- The Japan Automobile 
Manufacturers' Association issued a report Tuesday [28 June] 
summing up pending issues in Japan-U.S. automobile trade, 
arguing that Japan's auto market is open. 
  The association said cooperation between Japanese and U.S. 
automobile and auto parts industries to enhance bilateral trade 
is bearing fruit. 
  It said the report was compiled on the occasion of the 
resumption of Japan-U.S. negotiations for a new bilateral trade 
"framework." 
  The report said Japanese automakers are continuing efforts 
to 
increase procurement from U.S. auto parts makers. 
  In referring to a sales drive in Japan by the "big three" 
U.S. automakers, General Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co. and 
Chrysler Corp., the report said those firms still need to step 
up efforts to sell more vehicles. 
  It said the U.S. automakers have not developed small 
vehicles 
with an engine capacity of less than 2000 cc which account for 
more than 80 percent of the Japanese auto market. 
  The association said an English version of the report will 
be 
distributed in the United States later. 

</TEXT>

