<H3> <TI>   Reports on Issues Related to Deregulation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reports on Issues Related to Deregulation </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Nature of Economy To Change </H4>

<F P=102> OW2806031694 Tokyo KYODO in English 0255 GMT 28 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2806031694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 28 KYODO -- Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata 
said Tuesday [28 June] the deregulation package unveiled by the 
government the same day will change the nature of Japan's 
economy and show the direction in which the country should be 
heading. 
  Speaking at the administrative reform promotion 
headquarters, 
Hata said the package will be approved by the succeeding cabinet 
as soon as possible. 
  The current political scene remains mired in confusion in 
the 
wake of the Hata cabinet's resignation announcement on Saturday. 
  The scheme, compiled by the headquarters, contains 279 
deregulatory measures in the fields of real estate, financial 
services, information and telecommunications. 
  The plan was prepared in line with the government's 
market-access program announced in March to boost imports and 
spur domestic demand. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

