<H3> <TI>   Political Situation Report From Tokyo Continues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Political Situation Report From Tokyo Continues </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Hata `Likely To Meet Murayama </H4>

<F P=102> OW2806000494 Tokyo KYODO in English 2356 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2806000494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 28 KYODO -- The ruling coalition is 
likely to accept an overture from the Social Democratic Party 
(SDP) [Social Democratic Party of Japan -- SDPJ] and stage a 
meeting between Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata and SDP Chairman 
Tomiichi Murayama to discuss forming a new government, political 
sources said Tuesday. 
  Murayama and Masayoshi Takemura, New Party Sakigake head and 
a former chief cabinet secretary, agreed Monday that the next 
government should be a "dove," or soft-line government, based on 
an agreed policy outline. 
  Takemura, who is critical of what he views as high-handed 
leadership by Shinseito and Komeito within the coalition, made 
it clear that his party has no plans to reconcile with the group 
and urged Murayama to head the new government. 
  In a separate meeting, Yohei Kono, president of the main 
opposition Liberal Democratic Party (LDP), proposed a trilateral 
meeting with Murayama and Takemura for a breakthrough pact. 
  Takemura said Sakigake wants to serve as bridge between the 
LDP and the SDP in forming an alliance between the one-time 
archrivals. 
  Murayama and Kono agreed on the need to elect a new premier 
Tuesday. The current regular Diet session expires Wednesday. 
  Murayama and Kono also concurred in jointly taking "heavy 
responsibility" for breaking the current political standoff 
following the resignation of Hata and his cabinet on Saturday 
prior to an impending no-confidence vote against his minority 
cabinet tabled by the LDP in the House of Representatives. 
  Hata is the sixth prime minister in Japan in five years. 
None of the parties has a majority in the lower house. 
  The ruling coalition had earlier said it will wait for the 
SDP's initiative for fresh talks on a policy agreement before 
any high- stakes meeting between the party heads. 
  The SDP's policy-making board, on the other hand, endorsed 
the joint policy platform with Sakigake and called on the 
coalition to make a formal response to its proposal for the 
Murayama-Hata talks by 11 AM [0200 GMT] Tuesday. 
  Within the LDP, a growing number of party members are 
tilting 
toward a partnership with the SDP, party sources said. 
  The LDP had been in power since 1955 until last August when 
the then coalition of Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa, which 
included the SDP and Sakigake, took power. 
  But former Foreign Minister Michio Watanabe, an LDP faction 
leader, is opposed to an alliance with the SDP and called for a 
team up with Hata's Shinseito and Komeito, the key parties in 
the coalition. 
  Within the SDP, a left-wing group led by Murayama is said to 
be in favor of a tie-up with the LDP. 
  However, a right-wing group, including Secretary General 
Wataru Kubo, the No. 2 leader in the party, is seeking the 
return of the SDP to the coalition, party sources said. 
  The SDP earlier made a decision at a meeting of its 
decision- 
making central committee in May that it will not form a 
coalition with the LDP. 
  The SDP walked out from the coalition in April in protest 
against the formation of a parliamentary group by other 
coalition partners, excluding the SDP, shortly after the 
election of Hata as prime minister in the Diet. The SDP's 
departure forced Hata to launch the first minority government in 
39 years. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

