<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Political Situation Report From Tokyo Continues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Political Situation Report From Tokyo Continues </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Hata Calls for Diet Extension </H4>

<F P=102> OW2806134894 Tokyo KYODO in English 1332 GMT 28 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2806134894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 28 KYODO -- Outgoing Prime Minister 
Tsutomu Hata on Tuesday [28 June] called for extending the 
current parliamentary session beyond its deadline of Wednesday 
to enable the Diet to pick a new prime minister. 
  "It is inconceivable that the Diet should end its session 
before a new cabinet has been formed," said Hata, who announced 
Saturday his intention to resign along with his entire cabinet. 
Hata remains in office until his replacement is picked. 
  Hata made the comments as his ruling coalition is stepping 
up 
its bid to woo the Social Democratic Party (SDP) [SDPJ -- Social 
Democratic Party of Japan] back into its fold to create a 
stable, majority government. 
  The House of Representatives is to convene a plenary session 
at 10 a.m. Wednesday. 
  However, it remains unclear whether the lower chamber will 
be 
able to vote on a successor to Hata on Wednesday in view of 
intensifying parliamentary maneuverings by both the coalition 
and the no. 1 opposition Liberal Democratic Party to win over 
the socialists to their respective camps. 
  A source at the lower house's Diet steering committee, "it 
is 
in line with common sense that we should extend the Diet session 
by about a week until the second week of July, while seeking to 
pick a successor before the Naples Summit begins (July 8)." 
  Some LDP executives are trying to form a new coalition 
government comprising the LDP, SDP and new party Sakigake by 
forcing a vote during Wednesday's Diet session, while preventing 
the coalition from buying time to convince the SDP to return to 
its fold, Diet sources said. 
  "The coalition would not be able to extend the Diet if the 
LDP and SDP, which contains the proponents of an SDP-LDP 
alliance, jointly opposes such an extension," the source said. 
  In such an eventuality, the Diet would be forced to close 
its 
session temporarily and then hold an extraordinary session to 
pick a new premier and approve a bill defining the new 300 
single-seat constituencies, the sources said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

