<H3> <TI>   Business Leader Wants U.S. Interest Rates Hiked </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Business Leader Wants U.S. Interest Rates Hiked </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2706043694 Tokyo KYODO in English 0423 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2706043694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 27 KYODO -- A prominent businessman 
said Monday [27 June] Japan should urge the United States to 
raise interest rates and cut its deficit in order to cap the 
sharp appreciation of the yen against the dollar. 
  In a statement released Monday, Takeshi Nagano, president of 
the Japan Federation of Employers Association, said he is 
worried about the impact on the economy of the dollar's collapse 
and the political turmoil resulting from Prime Minister Tsutomu 
Hata's resignation. 
  Nagano warned an excessive appreciation of the yen could 
kill 
the Japanese manufacturing sector. 
  He called on the government for a speedy stimulation of 
domestic demand through deregulation and the opening of Japanese 
markets to imports. 
  The dollar temporarily plummeted to a new post World War II 
lows of 99.50 yen Monday morning in Tokyo. 

</TEXT>

