<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Business Leaders Wary of Yen's Surge </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Business Leaders Wary of Yen's Surge </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2706114094 Tokyo KYODO in English 1124 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2706114094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 27 KYODO -- Japanese business leaders 
voiced anxiety Monday [27 June] about the yen's vigorous surge 
against the U.S. dollar in recent days, fearing a fallout on the 
fragile economy. 
  Many leaders pinpointed yet another political crisis 
triggered by the resignation of Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata on 
Saturday as a factor which drove the yen above the 100-to-the 
dollar level in Monday dealings in Tokyo. 
  They expressed hopes that the political tempest will be 
calmed and the yen stabilized, while calling for boosted joint 
intervention by major economic powers. 
  Kosaku Inaba, chairman of the Japan Chamber of Commerce and 
Industry, said the yen's surge is "a regrettable matter both for 
the Japanese and global economy." 
  Other leaders said the yen's renewed strength would rid the 
Japanese economy of the little vitality it has to recover. 
  Even officials in the electric power and retail sectors, 
which can benefit from a stronger yen, are worried that high-yen 
drawbacks will outweigh merits. 
  In the long term, the leaders also said, the high yen will 
accelerate the hollowing out of Japanese industry, encouraging 
further shifts to overseas production and boosting unemployment. 
  To bring the yen under control, the business community urged 
an end to the political turmoil and more powerful actions by 
financial authorities in major countries. 
  Takeshi Nagano, president of the Japan Federation of 
Employers Associations, noted the United States could take 
measures to stop the dollar's fall, such as reducing the budget 
deficit and a raising interest rates. 
  Itochu Corp. President Minoru Murofushi also suggested the 
Bank of Japan lower the official discount rate to discourage 
yen-buyers. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

