<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fujii: Tokyo To Take `Aggressive' Action on Yen </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Fujii: Tokyo To Take `Aggressive' Action on Yen </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2706050994 Tokyo KYODO in English 0502 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2706050994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 27 KYODO -- Japan will take 
"aggressive" action to stem the yen's rise in cooperation with 
the Group of Seven (G-7) nations, Finance Minister Hirohisa 
Fujii told reporters Monday [27 June]. 
  Fujii described the dollar's fall in Tokyo below 100 yen as 
"speculative" and said, "rapid movements are undesirable and 
this is a consensus among G-7 nations." 
  Fujii said G-7 partners are communicating on whether to take 
joint measures as they did last Friday, when the dollar fell 
below 100 yen in New York. 
  As for Japan, Fujii said, "we will tenaciously take utmost 
efforts" to defend the dollar against the yen. 
  Market sources said the bank of Japan bought billions of 
dollars when the Tokyo market opened Monday, after watching the 
dollar plunge below 100 yen in earlier trading in Sydney. 
  Asked if Japan's political turmoil contributed to the yen's 
rise, Fujii just repeated the movements are "speculative." 
  Fujii declined to comment on possible joint G-7 actions on 
credit policies, saying, "monetary measures are for the central 
bank to decide." 
  When the dollar tumbled in may on a broad front and nearly 
sank below 100 yen, G-7 nations intervened in currency markets 
and also took action on credit policies. 
  The United States raised its key rates, Germany cut its key 
rates, other European nations followed suit and Japan maintained 
a loose stance on the money market. 
  Higher U.S. rates and lower rates in other nations will help 
the dollar become stronger as dollar assets will become 
favorable. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-30612 </DOCNO>
