<H3> <TI>   MITI Seeks Action for Stable Currency Market </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    MITI Seeks Action for Stable Currency Market </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2806031894 Tokyo KYODO in English 0308 GMT 28 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2806031894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 28 KYODO -- International Trade and 
Industry Minister [MITI] Eijiro Hata said Tuesday [28 June] he 
has asked the monetary authorities to take action to stabilize 
the currency market. 
  Steps should be taken so that a burgeoning pickup of the 
Japanese economy will be sustained and shifted to a full 
recovery, Hata told reporters. 
  Hata said he explained "the voice" of Japan's industrial 
sectors struggling under the unmitigated strength of the yen 
when he met with Finance Minister Hirohisa Fujii earlier in the 
day. 
  Fujii replied Japan is prepared to take action in concert 
with other Group of Seven (G-7) industrial countries, Hata said. 
  He said he has heard that the currency issue will be taken 
up 
at the upcoming G-7 summit in Naples, Italy. 
  The dollar sank to a new global low of 99.50 yen in Monday's 
Tokyo trading momentarily. 

</TEXT>

